text: This artifact was commissioned by Ross, Jono, Jacob and Alex for their mothers to talk about their parents and how they impacted their lives. Hi, I'm Derek from Artifact. And today I spoke with Susan and Cindy about their mother, Shirley, their memories with her and her impact on their life. We talked about their early childhood and growing up in a house full of laughter, curiosity, and maybe most of all, music, getting older and witnessing the curiosity and compassion that Shirley had toured the world and how they dealt with the most challenging times in her life to maintain their strong relationship all the way through having children of their own. Hello. I'm Susan Shannon, and I am Cindy Paul. I am the younger daughter of Shirley Cohen. So Susan and Cindy, thank you so much for joining me today to have this conversation about your mother, Shirley. I suppose if we want to talk a little bit about your childhood with her and your adolescence, we should start from the very beginning. And I was wondering if you could each talk a little bit about some of your earliest memories of your mother and what your life was like in your early childhood. One of my earliest memories is of mom and my expecting a visit from my mother's brothers from upstate New York. And when they came, they had with them a little toy table and chairs set for me. So the purpose for their visit was to deliver that set. And I remember it all very clearly. I remember the table and chairs. It was very exciting. It was almost magical because I just did not have a lot of toys and other objects in my life. And this was really a major moment. Cindy, do you want to talk about a memory of yours? Yeah, actually, I think it is. Actually. My first memory was being in our living room. We lived in an apartment building in Newark, New Jersey. Mom and dad both worked in Newark at that time. And when I was two years old, I remember there was a birthday party. And I don't know if it was my birthday party or Susan's birthday party, but mom was a music major, and there was always our piano, her piano in the house, and she played the piano and she sang all the time. And she taught us songs and music with both of our parents was a really big deal. And I just remember standing with my back to the piano and looking out into the living room, and there was a brightly colored paper tablecloth on the floor, all set up for this birthday party. And I knew something special was happening. And mom was very big, always on celebrating milestones. So one of my first memories of her really, I think my first memory ever is of one of these milestone things happening and mom being the one to make that happen. You talked a little bit about this with the music. But what are some of the things that you did together as a family or some of the just traditions or activities that you shared with her when you were both children? Oh, there were lots well, of course, holidays were celebrated. And in our case, because our parents were of a mixed marriage, my father being Jewish, my mother being Christian, we got to celebrate all the holidays. So yeah, Christmas and Hanukkah. It was just a bonanza. And we celebrated Passover with my father's. Parents used to go to Seders there, and we celebrated Easter Sunday, generally home with mom sometimes we did go upstate New York to be with her family. And the holidays were a big deal. And it was very food focused and just being together. And everybody would usually dress up a little bit. Nothing major but some nicer clothing. We used to get Easter dresses. Well, for Easter. Yeah, pretty Easter dress. We did the whole thing. We dyed the eggs. Mom would get the egg dying kits, and she'd make a big deal of it. We dye the eggs. And later when we had a little backyard, she'd hide the eggs and we would look for them. We had an Easter egg Hunt. One thing, though, I have to say, she never got the solid chocolate bunnies. I'll say this politely. They were very frugal. So we always got the hollow chocolate bunnies. Other people I know got the solid chocolate bunnies, but we didn't. We got the hollow chocolate bunnies, but we did get the chocolate bunnies and the jelly beans. Mom loved jelly beans. Always loved jelly beans. This is true. Very true. Jelly beans were a big deal. She used to keep them in a pretty little bowl on a table right by the front door so that guests coming and going could grab a couple of jelly beans. Yeah. And just as far as the music, she was always singing, she would do the dishes and she'd be singing flammy to the Moon and Viokandios and Red Roses for a Blue Lady. And I can remember so many of these songs because she sang them. And she taught us a lot of songs. She had been a teacher, like a K to five teacher, so she had all her stuff from when she was a teacher. And there were just always records in the house. We had always tons of records. Just always lots of music. And our dad loved music, too. So there was actually they met in a library listening to music. That's how they met. So there was lots and lots of music in our house. Always. And Susan and I, we would sing together all the time, too. The two of us, when we go on trips, we would sit in the back of the car. We would sing together. I remember one trip, we took a little portable record player and bought all our Beatles albums. We knew all the words. We could sing all the songs together, and they loved it. They never told us, don't be quiet. They never told us, be quiet or you're making too much money. Whatever. They were always totally cool with any kind of music and singing and playing records that we wanted to do. Yeah. When we were teenagers, records were a really big deal. And we both had stereo systems in our bedroom. And we used to really crank it up. And nobody ever said, turn it down. It was just fine. For me. It was the exact opposite because our dad would play his stereo in the living room every night, and I'd be trying to fall asleep and I have to yell down at him, dad, turn down the stereo. Finally he got headphones. And that solves the problem. All of our abodes were small. We lived in a small apartment in a 15 story apartment building in Newark. And for one year we lived in a small upper floor of a two family home. And then when we were Susan was going into fifth grade, and I was going into third, and she was going to 6th grade, and I was going in fourth grade, we moved to a very small house, a single family house, but every place we ever lived was very small. You're telling these stories in your household was clearly so full of life and just the sense of adventure, having different experiences, and really valuing those. There's a story from both of your questionnaires that you each mentioned that I would love for you to tell me about, which is that it sounds like you had a very interesting experience with the seance that your mother held with you and the neighborhood kids. I don't know how it came to be, but one night, my dad must have been in the hospital at the time because he wasn't there. And we had some friends, my sister and I on our street, and I think like a Saturday night. And they came down to our house. It was a family of three children, and they came to our house. And somehow we wound up sitting at the kitchen table, and mom is leading us in a seance. It was bizarre. We're sitting at this table. She's completely into it. We have no idea if she's kidding, if she's serious. It was so out of character for her. And she's leading the seance, and we're hearing noises and knocking and different noises. And then the real kicker was that one of these girls had I'm not going to say the name, but she had a nickname, and everybody knew her by this nickname and didn't know her real name. She just had this nickname. And our mother, during this seance, mom said something about hearing or being connecting to a relative and aunt of this girl and saying, this is the name of this aunt. And our friend completely flipped out because that name that my mother said was actually the girl's real name. She was named for an aunt who died young, and none of us knew it. So the whole thing that went on for weeks after that because we said to our mother, how did you know that name? Where did that come from? But before we get to that part, when this happened, mom became completely hysterical at our belief in this whole situation and disbelief. And she just kept laughing. And it was a little kind of weird. It was very weird. And I brought her into the bathroom and sat her down on the toilet seat, and I slapped her across the face hard as I could because I was convinced that there was some kind of a spirit perhaps inside of her, and we needed to get rid of it. And I'll just never forget slapping her. And I mean, the minute my hand touched her face, things changed completely. She stopped laughing. And I don't even remember exactly what happened after that. I just remember that I slapped her and she stopped laughing and everything was okay. But I have always thought about that my whole life. That when I was about, oh, I must have been 13. I slapped my mother across the face hard as could be. And that's just kind of a weird thing to do. She wasn't mad. It was pretty wild, really was. When you look back with the perspective that you have today, what would you say are some of the main things that your mother tried to just instill in you as values, as people when you were young and she was raising you. I think the overriding thing with my mother was to be kind to other people, to just be a kind, decent person. That was really important to her, one of many things. But I think that was one of the most important. Education was a basic family value. It was more than a family value with our whole lives revolved around becoming educated. My parents were both Masters level people and work in professions. Both had to do with teaching in different ways. And it was important our report cards and it was important. We knew we needed to do our homework. There was never any nonsense about it. And I remember one time I failed a semester of mathematics, which was my weakest subject, and that was a big no. And there weren't many in our household growing up, but that was a big no. And mom and dad sat me down and explained to me that this was not acceptable and expected never to have to see a grade like that on my report card. And of course, they never did. I was not happy with the grade myself. It was a bad semester. They were incredibly tolerant of people that had problems. They took people in. There were people in our family, friends over the years, people who had gotten divorced, people who are estranged from their families, different people, and they would welcome them into our homes. Susan and I were not always happy about that, but they did that. And they were very conscious of people that were forsaken people that were downtrodden. They were very sensitive to racial issues. They were extremely conscious about racial issues. There were activists. We would have nights when they're amazing, interesting, fascinating friends. It was like a salon of intellectual. People would come and party at our house, and they'd be drinking and smoking. And Susan and I would just like, take it all in because these people were just so interesting. And they were all very progressive and like minded people and very political and people to this day. I mean, just recently, a guy that was on our street a year younger than I was, very sweet, nice guy, very smart, successful. And he just said something on Facebook about how he delivered the newspaper to my parents'house on Fridays. He would come and pick up the money from the paper delivery and that he would have these great conversations with them and that he just loved them. And they were so positive with him and reinforcing. And he was just a kid back then. And lots of our friends will say that that our house was the house you could always come to and you're always welcome, no matter what side of the track you were from or where you were from. They didn't care as long as you were a nice person. But even not so nice people, they were tolerant of. So that's something they really instilled in us. And they really had special interest in our friends. Yes. They really would set aside the time to sit and talk with them and get to know them and make them comfortable. And that was not something many parents did at that time. People would be nice, certainly, and welcome you into their homes and so on. But my parents really went a couple of steps further. I would say Cindy and I both grew up having friends. And still to this day, we both have good friends in our lives. And that's largely because our parents really valued that. It was many good times with many interesting, fascinating people and people who weren't interesting and fascinating as well. There was something to be gained from everybody. They had respect as you got older and maybe became more tuned into those conversations the adults were having. And the way you just described, how did your relationship with your mother change as you got older? Became teenagers, developed their own interests and opinions and things like that? Well, what really happened in our adolescence with mom was she became well, she really was mentally ill. She really had emotional problems, and her world started closing in on her, and she wouldn't go places. It really started when we were teenagers, and she was diagnosed with fibromyalgia, which causes full body pain. And it's like one of those invisible diseases and a lot of doctors and everything will say, well, one of the things to do to combat it is to lose your body and to move. She just did the exact opposite. She just wouldn't do physical things. She stopped driving, and that was very difficult, I think, for both of us. And we were extremely independent, both of us mom worked once. She worked. She worked very long hours. She worked late. She was not the mom who was home and have dinner ready, and she was not the mom who could get you to your west and after school or come to your base, your softball game or your track meet or whatever. And then as she got ill, that was even more of a thing. She just wasn't available to us in ways that she had been when we were younger, and that was difficult. But the plus side of it is we were both very independent. We both left home when we were basically 17, maybe came back in between College a little bit, but we were pretty much out of there at a very young age. We both graduated high school year early. Susan did it first, and I did a second. So each of us, after our junior years, we graduated from high school and went to College. So something was pushing us out, and I could probably spend a million hours of therapy trying to figure that out. But I was not happy. That whole part of her when we were older and in terms of our father during that period, he had a severe bout of depression himself. In fact, I think his was first yeah, his was first when we were younger, and I remember it vividly. And then he got better and he was fine. He then was able to carry out all of his fatherly husband responsibilities. And then once he got better and was able to handle things, then that's when mom fell apart. So, yeah, it was rough at times with both of them and for all four of us, but we still always maintained a closeness that we absolutely carried throughout our adulthood. And with them in our adulthood. They were both very involved with their grandchildren. Our children just always coming down for the weekend and just couldn't get enough of their grandkids, which was wonderful because it kind of maybe made up for the times that weren't so wonderful when Cindy and I were little, because at that point in their lives, they were older and more, I would say, satisfied with themselves and life. And we're really able to give a lot to both of our kids. It was a good time. Very true. Unfortunately, I feel like we could, as you were saying, spend many more hours talking about this, but our time here is coming to an end. Before we do, I want to make sure there wasn't anything that we haven't gotten to yet that you wanted to make absolutely sure as part of this conversation. I couldn't get started on it. There's too many things to get started on. Well, I just want to say that I remember for their 50th wedding anniversary, they gave themselves a party with the family. We all went out to dinner, and I think we had like a separate room in the restaurant. And I remember my parents standing up and there must have been music playing and they just started waltzing together. And it was so sweet. They were so tender with each other. They really just really adored each other completely. It was right after really during our father had had a quintuple bypass surgery and a very broken leg. He was in the hospital and rehab for many months. He was very sick. And that party, that was in 2004. And it was like a coming out for him, basically, of being able to sort of get past this whole many months of recovering from the broken leg and the quintuple bypass surgery that he had to have before they would do the surgery on the broken leg. So. Yeah, that was special. I remember that. Yeah. So we always like to end these episodes with a direct address from the speakers to the people who it is recorded for. This was commissioned by both of your sons to sort of learn a little bit more about your parents and your family history. And I would love for both of you to just very briefly address them as if they were in the room with you right now. What would you say to them about your mother that you really want to impart and make sure that they know about her and the impact she's had on everybody's life? Well, I would say to them, boys, you were Mum's greatest dream come true. The four of you that their daughters grew up and had these wonderful sons, and you were their greatest wish, their dream come true. That's what I would say to them. Yeah. I would say to your boys and my boys, the four of them, fulfillment. Mom's probably greatest wish. Her daughters grow up and be healthy and happy and to have these wonderful grandsons for them. She took care of them. She spent so many hours babysitting and took care of them so well. I remember when they would come and stay in my house for a weekend, and it would give Alex and myself time to get out, and we would come in and it was if mom and dad were the main parents in the house, they just took the house over, took care of everything, and let Alec and I go do our fun stuff. And it was just so natural. It was like a continuation of my growing up with them in their house. We continued that process in my house as I became an adult and was raising my kids. And my kids would say the same thing. Mom and dad were just part of the family. I mean, we were just like an extended family living together. We spent that much time together and it was wonderful. Truly wonderful. And I thanked them from the bottom of my heart all the time that they were so there for us and so there for my kids. They were very special people. Very special people.

This artifact was commissioned by Ross, Jono, Jacob and Alex for their mothers to talk about their parents and how they impacted their lives. Hi, I'm Derek from Artifact. And today I spoke with Susan and Cindy about their mother, Shirley, their memories with her and her impact on their life.

We talked about their early childhood and growing up in a house full of laughter, curiosity, and maybe most of all, music, getting older and witnessing the curiosity and compassion that Shirley had toured the world and how they dealt with the most challenging times in her life to maintain their strong relationship all the way through having children of their own. Hello. I'm Susan Shannon, and I am Cindy Paul. I am the younger daughter of Shirley Cohen.

So Susan and Cindy, thank you so much for joining me today to have this conversation about your mother, Shirley. I suppose if we want to talk a little bit about your childhood with her and your adolescence, we should start from the very beginning. And I was wondering if you could each talk a little bit about some of your earliest memories of your mother and what your life was like in your early childhood.

One of my earliest memories is of mom and my expecting a visit from my mother's brothers from upstate New York. And when they came, they had with them a little toy table and chairs set for me. So the purpose for their visit was to deliver that set. And I remember it all very clearly. I remember the table and chairs. It was very exciting. It was almost magical because I just did not have a lot of toys and other objects in my life.

And this was really a major moment. Cindy, do you want to talk about a memory of yours? Yeah, actually, I think it is. Actually. My first memory was being in our living room. We lived in an apartment building in Newark, New Jersey. Mom and dad both worked in Newark at that time. And when I was two years old, I remember there was a birthday party.

And I don't know if it was my birthday party or Susan's birthday party, but mom was a music major, and there was always our piano, her piano in the house, and she played the piano and she sang all the time. And she taught us songs and music with both of our parents was a really big deal.

And I just remember standing with my back to the piano and looking out into the living room, and there was a brightly colored paper tablecloth on the floor, all set up for this birthday party. And I knew something special was happening. And mom was very big, always on celebrating milestones. So one of my first memories of her really, I think my first memory ever is of one of these milestone things happening and mom being the one to make that happen.

You talked a little bit about this with the music. But what are some of the things that you did together as a family or some of the just traditions or activities that you shared with her when you were both children? Oh, there were lots well, of course, holidays were celebrated. And in our case, because our parents were of a mixed marriage, my father being Jewish, my mother being Christian, we got to celebrate all the holidays. So yeah, Christmas and Hanukkah.

It was just a bonanza. And we celebrated Passover with my father's. Parents used to go to Seders there, and we celebrated Easter Sunday, generally home with mom sometimes we did go upstate New York to be with her family. And the holidays were a big deal. And it was very food focused and just being together. And everybody would usually dress up a little bit. Nothing major but some nicer clothing. We used to get Easter dresses. Well, for Easter. Yeah, pretty Easter dress.

We did the whole thing. We dyed the eggs. Mom would get the egg dying kits, and she'd make a big deal of it. We dye the eggs. And later when we had a little backyard, she'd hide the eggs and we would look for them. We had an Easter egg Hunt. One thing, though, I have to say, she never got the solid chocolate bunnies. I'll say this politely. They were very frugal. So we always got the hollow chocolate bunnies.

Other people I know got the solid chocolate bunnies, but we didn't. We got the hollow chocolate bunnies, but we did get the chocolate bunnies and the jelly beans. Mom loved jelly beans. Always loved jelly beans. This is true. Very true. Jelly beans were a big deal. She used to keep them in a pretty little bowl on a table right by the front door so that guests coming and going could grab a couple of jelly beans. Yeah.

And just as far as the music, she was always singing, she would do the dishes and she'd be singing flammy to the Moon and Viokandios and Red Roses for a Blue Lady. And I can remember so many of these songs because she sang them. And she taught us a lot of songs. She had been a teacher, like a K to five teacher, so she had all her stuff from when she was a teacher. And there were just always records in the house.

We had always tons of records. Just always lots of music. And our dad loved music, too. So there was actually they met in a library listening to music. That's how they met. So there was lots and lots of music in our house. Always. And Susan and I, we would sing together all the time, too. The two of us, when we go on trips, we would sit in the back of the car. We would sing together.

I remember one trip, we took a little portable record player and bought all our Beatles albums. We knew all the words. We could sing all the songs together, and they loved it. They never told us, don't be quiet. They never told us, be quiet or you're making too much money. Whatever. They were always totally cool with any kind of music and singing and playing records that we wanted to do. Yeah. When we were teenagers, records were a really big deal.

And we both had stereo systems in our bedroom. And we used to really crank it up. And nobody ever said, turn it down. It was just fine. For me. It was the exact opposite because our dad would play his stereo in the living room every night, and I'd be trying to fall asleep and I have to yell down at him, dad, turn down the stereo. Finally he got headphones. And that solves the problem. All of our abodes were small.

We lived in a small apartment in a 15 story apartment building in Newark. And for one year we lived in a small upper floor of a two family home. And then when we were Susan was going into fifth grade, and I was going into third, and she was going to 6th grade, and I was going in fourth grade, we moved to a very small house, a single family house, but every place we ever lived was very small.

You're telling these stories in your household was clearly so full of life and just the sense of adventure, having different experiences, and really valuing those. There's a story from both of your questionnaires that you each mentioned that I would love for you to tell me about, which is that it sounds like you had a very interesting experience with the seance that your mother held with you and the neighborhood kids.

I don't know how it came to be, but one night, my dad must have been in the hospital at the time because he wasn't there. And we had some friends, my sister and I on our street, and I think like a Saturday night. And they came down to our house. It was a family of three children, and they came to our house. And somehow we wound up sitting at the kitchen table, and mom is leading us in a seance. It was bizarre.

We're sitting at this table. She's completely into it. We have no idea if she's kidding, if she's serious. It was so out of character for her. And she's leading the seance, and we're hearing noises and knocking and different noises. And then the real kicker was that one of these girls had I'm not going to say the name, but she had a nickname, and everybody knew her by this nickname and didn't know her real name.

And our friend completely flipped out because that name that my mother said was actually the girl's real name. She was named for an aunt who died young, and none of us knew it.

But before we get to that part, when this happened, mom became completely hysterical at our belief in this whole situation and disbelief. And she just kept laughing. I just remember that I slapped her and she stopped laughing and everything was okay. But I have always thought about that my whole life. That when I was about, oh, I must have been 13. I slapped my mother across the face hard as could be. And that's just kind of a weird thing to do. She wasn't mad. It was pretty wild, really was.

When you look back with the perspective that you have today, what would you say are some of the main things that your mother tried to just instill in you as values, as people when you were young and she was raising you. I think the overriding thing with my mother was to be kind to other people, to just be a kind, decent person. That was really important to her, one of many things. But I think that was one of the most important.

Education was a basic family value. It was more than a family value with our whole lives revolved around becoming educated. My parents were both Masters level people and work in professions. Both had to do with teaching in different ways. And it was important our report cards and it was important. We knew we needed to do our homework. There was never any nonsense about it. And there weren't many in our household growing up, but that was a big no. I was not happy with the grade myself. It was a bad semester. They were incredibly tolerant of people that had problems. They took people in.

There were people in our family, friends over the years, people who had gotten divorced, people who are estranged from their families, different people, and they would welcome them into our homes. Susan and I were not always happy about that, but they did that. And they were very conscious of people that were forsaken people that were downtrodden. They were very sensitive to racial issues. They were extremely conscious about racial issues. There were activists.

We would have nights when they're amazing, interesting, fascinating friends. It was like a salon of intellectual. People would come and party at our house, and they'd be drinking and smoking. And Susan and I would just like, take it all in because these people were just so interesting. And they were all very progressive and like minded people and very political and people to this day.

I mean, just recently, a guy that was on our street a year younger than I was, very sweet, nice guy, very smart, successful. And he just said something on Facebook about how he delivered the newspaper to my parents'house on Fridays. He would come and pick up the money from the paper delivery and that he would have these great conversations with them and that he just loved them. And they were so positive with him and reinforcing.
